02895cam a2200421 i 20161228113748.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||130912t2013    miua    ob   s001 0 eng d  a2013020523  a9780472119028q(hardback)  a9780472029549q(e-book)7 a10.3998/mpub.4773062  aMiUbengcMiU  an-us---an-us-inan-us-mn00aJS331b.K73 201300a320.60973/0917322231 aKraus, Neil,d1968-10aMajoritarian cities :bpolicy making and inequality in urban politics /cNeil Kraus. 1aAnn Arbor :bUniversity of Michigan Press,c[2013]  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.  a"Neil Kraus evaluates both the influence of public opinion on local policy-making and the extent to which public policy addresses economic and social inequalities. Drawing on several years of fieldwork and multiple sources of data, including surveys and polls; initiatives, referenda, and election results; government documents; focus groups; interviews; and a wide assortment of secondary sources, Kraus presents case studies of two Midwestern cities, Minneapolis, Minnesota, and Gary, Indiana. Specifically, he focuses on several major policy decisions in recent decades concerning education, law enforcement, and affordable housing in Minneapolis; and education and riverboat casino development in Gary. Kraus finds that, on these issues, local officials frequently take action that reflects public opinion, yet the resulting policies often fail to meet the needs of the disadvantaged or ameliorate the effects of concentrated poverty. In light of citizens' current attitudes, he concludes that if patterns of inequality are to be more effectively addressed, scholars and policymakers must transform the debate about the causes and effects of inequality in urban and metropolitan settings"--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aLocal governmentzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aMetropolitan governmentzUnit